The `sort` method of `Collections` is *stable*. That means, it will  not change the order of two objects that compare as equal. 

`BigDecimal.compareTo` regards `0.00`,  `0.0000`, and `0` as equal to each other. The values `123`, `123.00`, `123.000` are another example. So, in your example, if `0` precedes `000.000` before the sort, `0` will precede `000.000` after the sort. If `000.000` precedes `0` before the sort, `000.000` will precede `0` after the sort. If that is an issue for you, you can create a custom [`Comparator`](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/11/docs/api/java.base/java/util/Comparator.html), which might use the [`scale` method of BigDecimal](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/11/docs/api/java.base/java/math/BigDecimal.html#scale()). Another option is to create a custom class, which implements [`Comparable`](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/11/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/Comparable.html).

